With Halloween around the corner I&#39;ve been getting some spooky JS bugs. This one I can&#39;t wrap my head around and have been unable to debug at all. Essentially, I&#39;m using Electron, and when I observe a variable in the renderer process it&#39;s fine, but when I call it on the main process it is missing an entire key value pair:

```
function someFunction(someVariable) {
  console.log(someVariable)
}

console.log(myVariable) // { key1: value1 }
myVariable.key2 = value2
console.log(myVariable) // { key1: value1, key2: value2 }
someFunction(myVariable) // { key1: value1 }
console.log(myVariable) // { key1: value1, key2: value2 }
```

I have absolutely no idea how this is possible. From the view of the event emitter this is basically the same as calling a normal function. The object is single use and not referenced elsewhere so there&#39;s no way that it has managed to change in between `console.log` and `someFunction`.

Restarting the node process and refreshing the renderer page have no effect.

**Update:**

I&#39;ve managed to get a temporary workaround that works for a few minutes before reverting to the above behaviour once more.

If I do:
```
